  "paragraphs": [
    "Focusing on artists who came after jazz musician Sun Ra, working between the 1970s and the present day, I highlight the ways in which ancient Egypt is remembered and reimagined in Afrofuturism within the Afrodiasporic community of the US. This is particularly readable because Afrofuturist narratives are widely and influentially spread. Available with this essay is a Spotify playlist featuring the music discussed. Afrofuturism in the twenty-first century is expressed in metaphysics, religion, speculative philosophy, and philosophy of science and technology. Jones This article, however, explores Afrofuturism as a form of speculative fiction addressing contemporary concerns relevant to Black African communities and the African diaspora. Afrofuturism often involves rejecting the definition of the past solely based on the traumas of slavery and the transatlantic slave trade. Afrofuturists emphasize that such retellings are necessary. They argue that the way the past is understood is inherently political because it is produced and sustained by hegemonic institutions, including universities and museums. From an Afrofuturist perspective, and as is explored later in this article, the ways in which futures are created and imagined are equally political.",
    "The Afrodiasporic community in California identifies with the Egyptian god Osiris, linking social justice and progress to ancient Egyptian royalty. Janelle Monáe is an example of a prominent feminist Afrofuturist artist. Her work explores themes and ideas that intersect with ancient Egyptian culture. Enslaved people and robots are often viewed as analogous, neither fully human nor fully safe in the eyes of their masters. They are both subjected to forced labor. Some Afrofuturist artists subvert this narrative.",
    "The androids presented by The Egyptian Lover and Erykah Badu embody multiple layers of time, challenging their relationship with servitude. Sun Ra was mentioned by both Om'mas Keith and Taz Arnold in the same interview. Ray Fuego, a Dutch artist, describes himself as \"Son of the Sun\" in his biography available on Spotify.",
    "During the band members' performance at Aegyptiaca's (8) 2024 Back on the Planet: An Egyptological Perspective event, ancient Egyptian monuments appeared on stage: the Great Pyramid of Giza, sphinxes, columns, temples, and statues. Maurice White, the leader of the band, introduced the kalimba into their music. The kalimba is an instrument traditionally used by the Shona people in southern Africa. The kalimba used by Earth, Wind & Fire underwent an Afrofuturist transformation, becoming electronic. This reinterpretation drew from an ancient African sound. In the same vein, the 808 drum machine, first popularized in the 1980s, enabled The Egyptian Lover, a pioneer in electronic music, to create a futuristic, synthetic sound with electro beats and laser effects, while reimagining ancient Egypt.",
    "Artists can create a sense of futurism in their music by incorporating elements from earlier periods through sampling. She addresses systemic exploitation in contemporary society by referring to her allies as \"children of the Matrix,\" drawing inspiration from science fiction. Amen Khum Ra, a spiritual artist and Kemetist, performs the \"rhyme from old ancient times\" later in the song. In this chant, the language of ancient Egypt is performed. As a result, the artist's interpretation of the time and place in ancient Egypt becomes accessible to the listener. Amen Khum Ra states that the first part of the chant translates to: \"We are the brightest light, born from the deepest darkness, children of the divine Mother and Father, true right and exact. Open the way, shining ones, open the way, listen to these divine words I speak.\" To the ear of the Egyptologist, the translation by Steinskog is notable for its exploration of Afrofuturism. For further information on Kemetism, refer to Harrison's work. Amen Khum Ra's original post on Myspace is no longer available, but its translation can be found online.",
    "The use of w50 is inaccurate and outdated. It may obscure the intended message of the artist, but Egyptological precision is not the primary goal of the song. Tobias was 52 years old. van Veen has argued that this question leads to one of the main objectives of Afrofuturism: creating temporal interventions that break with, remodel, or revise the timeline to remake a recursive future as part of transformative strategies that impact the boundaries of \"authentic\" Black culture. In van Veen's analysis, Sun Ra is considered an extraterrestrial being from a distant future, who arrives in the present from ancient Egypt, thus creating an alternate timeline. You haven't provided any text to correct. If the past, present, and future are part of the same cycle, then all time blends. As Ras G clarified: \"You say futurists, I say timeless.\" This perspective on time frequently recurs in Afrofuturist music. The playful cover art of The Egyptian Lover's album \"Egyptian Lover\" (1986) weaves together three distinct eras.",
    "After the robot's introduction, the theatre transports its audience into a future that combines elements of the 1940s, a distant future, and ancient Egypt. For instance, Egyptologists continue to use the term “canopic jar” to refer to the receptacles that held the viscera removed from the body during mummification. Despite this, Egyptology now agrees that these vessels have no connection to the city of Canopus or its Osiris cult.",
    "The speculative aspects of Egyptological research are evident. In museums, Egyptologists showcase tentative facial reconstructions of embalmed Egyptian bodies, which seem to bring viewers face to face with the dead, erasing time and distance. This is also reflected in archaeological publications featuring drawings or 3D models of reconstructed temples in landscapes, intentionally left desolate to avoid introducing unsubstantiated elements. It can be argued that 86 Howard Street is a significant location. “Synthesis of a Vocal Sound,”  ”  Gillam, \"Inhabiting the Landscape\", 167 Labrousse, 90. The Pyramids of the Queens. Although the radically revisionist approach of Afrofuturist art is challenging to reconcile with the general goals of Egyptology, Egyptologists are continually reevaluating ancient Egyptian history."
